For {= operator_system =}+ U.S. hospital systems, hospitals, or healthcare delivery operators, supply an operator-controlled source for a current acute hospital-at-home program, with {= url =}+ proof URLs per operator. Similar labels such as home-hospital, hospital care at home, or advanced care at home can count when the page supports the same care model. Each URL must prove the named operator's own program, not just show that the operator appears in a CMS/QualityNet list or third-party article.

Proof URLs must be on the operator's own website or another operator-controlled official channel. CMS/QualityNet pages, vendor pages, policy explainers, third-party news or directories, and press-wire republications do not count.

Lower-acuity home services such as home health, remote patient monitoring, chronic-care management, hospice, palliative care, telehealth-only visits, and post-discharge recovery support do not count unless the page also shows an acute hospital-level or inpatient-level program. Program labels vary; the label is less important than the hospital-at-home care model the page actually supports.

Requirements:
- The page must communicate (possibly via URL among other page cues) that it is an official source surface controlled by the named operator.
- The page must present the named operator as currently offering or operating the program itself; a facility listed under a parent system does not count as a separate operator unless the page gives that facility its own program/operator framing.
- The page must support an acute hospital-level or inpatient-level care model delivered at home, rather than a lower-acuity home service.
- The page must expose concrete hospital-style care operations, such as admission or ED/inpatient eligibility, physician or hospitalist rounding, daily in-person clinician visits, 24/7 monitoring or team access, IV medication, labs, imaging, oxygen, or comparable services delivered during the at-home admission.
